(8) Any clerk who knowingly issues a marriage license to any persons prohibited by this chapter from marrying shall be fined not less than five hundred nor more than one thousand dollars, and removed from office by the judgment of the court in which he is convicted.

(9) Any clerk who knowingly issues a marriage license in violation of his duty under this chapter shall be fined not more than one thousand dollars.

(10) If any deputy clerk or any person other than a county clerk knowingly issues a marriage license in violation of this chapter, but not for a prohibited marriage, he shall be fined not more than one thousand dollars, and if he knowingly issues a license for a marriage prohibited by this chapter he shall be fined not more than one thousand dollars or imprisoned not more than one year, or both.

(11) Any person who violates any of the provisions of KRS 402.090 shall be fined not less than ten nor more than one hundred dollars for each offense.

(12) Any county clerk who violates any of the provisions of KRS 402.110 or 402.230 shall be fined not less than twenty nor more than fifty dollars. (Subsection (12) amended, 1950, c. 11)

(13) Any person who violates any of the provisions of KRS 402.120 to 402.200 by disclosing any matter of confidential nature shall be fined one thousand dollars, which shall be paid to the applicant for a marriage license in lieu of damages. Upon failure to pay the fine, the defendant shall be imprisoned as for failure to pay any other fine.

(14) Any physician, laboratory representative, county clerk or applicant for a marriage license who violates any of the provisions of KRS 402.120 to 402.200, or makes any false representation of fact or identity, shall be fined not less than ten nor more than one hundred dollars, and imprisoned in the county jail for a term fixed by the jury.

(15) Any person failing to make the return required of him by KRS 402.220 shall be fined fifty dollars.

